  "why": "The paper designs mutations and explicit conformity checks to preserve plausibility at each mutation step (e.g., scoped semantic actions, preconditions, perspective/lighting/road-location checks, and using real-world entity resources). However, the design does not describe mechanisms that explicitly control or measure cumulative distortion across repeated fuzzing iterations (no tracking of perturbation magnitude relative to the original seed, nor use of a learned generator/restrictive distribution). The resource set is built from the prior real-world dataset and mutations are applied using those resources, which enforces per-step realism, but mutated tests are not described as being constrained relative to the original seed across multiple mutation rounds. Therefore the technique fits the \"Medium\" category: per-step plausibility preservation but no explicit cumulative-distortion control.",
  "evidence": "3.2 Semantic Mutations with semSensFuzz (p. 1960): \"Second, we associate a set of preconditions Prec with each mutation δ, specified in terms of the interp that defines whether δ is applicable to a given t. If Prec(interp) is not satisfied, then δ is not applicable to that test.\"; 4.1 semImFuzz Architecture (p. 1962): \"As a preprocessing step, semImFuzz parses the prior test set to build a resource set of available data, e.g. a list of all cars and their poses.\"; 4.3.1 Implementation — Conformity checks (p. 1963): \"we divide the images into quadrants and consider two images to be compatible if their vanishing points are in the same quadrant... if the entity does not have a median value within 5 units (~2%) of the median value of the base image target area, then it fails the conformity check.\"; 4.4.4 Discriminators for Conformity Checking (p. 1964): \"We explored this approach, training a binary classifier... The discriminator learned to differentiate between the classes, but could not differentiate conforming versus nonconforming images.\" These sections show explicit per-mutation plausibility measures but no mechanism to bound or account for cumulative distortion across repeated mutations."
